metadata.name: Growth One #27
metadata.description:
Growth One

by Daeinc
March 2022
  
A growth simulation of a virtual micro organism that follows simple rules. The organism starts with a few seed nodes, and it grows when the seed nodes and search nodes accept each other when they meet certain conditions. The organism loosely resembles structures found in nature such as coral reef or fungus. Do we embrace the beauty of its emerging structure or reject it because of pathogenic associations?  
  
Instructions:
  - The simulation may take some time to finish.
  - press [spacebar] - start/stop breathing animation
  - press [b] - alternative grey backgrounds
  - press [s] - export high resolution PNG image
  - press [p] - play or pause the entire animation
  - real time growth mode - You can simulate the growth in real-time by adding "realtime" parameter to the end of the URL in live view. (ex. https://ipfs.io/.../?fxhash=...&realtime)
  
License
CC-BY-NC 4.0
p5js library was used for html5 canvas codes. No modification other than bundling was made to the library. g.js library was referenced for vector graphics. canvas-sketch was used to build/bundle the project. Please refer to the included LICENSE.md for license information.

metadata.name: Waves and Ripples #125
metadata.description:
Waves and Ripples is an implementation of a continuous CA, where wave like behaviours are obtained from the influence of neighbour cells over the cell itself. Depeding on the connections config for each cell, different patterns will emerge, creating waves, ripples, or a mix of both. When single loop is on, the calculations and drawings are done at once, which makes for a more chaotic visual.
Best enjoyed in full-screen :) 

Click anywhere to restart

Features : 
  shrinkFactor : 3 types
  connectArray: 16 possibilities,
  extraConnection: 4 types,
  mutualNeighbour: 40% chance,
  singleLoop: 30% chance
  monoChromo:  15% chance

Inspired by Matt Pearson's book.

metadata.name: cLAZY MONSTER #23
metadata.description:
This project is Generative Layered PNGs files.

There are 11-Layers mixing together to make many unique 1/1 cLAZY MONSTER.

00-Background - 18 items
01-BackgroundComponent - 14 items
02-Body - 3 items
03-Clothes - 16 items
04-Face_Base - 1 item
05-Face_Level_1 - 20 items
06-Face_Level_2 - 21 items
07-Eyes - 14 items
08-Mouth - 7 items
09-Hands - 10 items
10-Nose - 11 items

So the maximum possibilities to be unique is
18x14x3x16x1x20x21x14x7x10x11 = 54,765,849,600 chances!

Good Luck, cLAZY MONSTER team!

metadata.name: AngrySquares.gif #3
metadata.description:
An experiment in GIF serialization on fxhash by Nate Donato, this collection features a generative animation that can be automatically saved as a high quality gif.  Playing with block color and simple motion, each iteration features a rapid animation of basic shapes fluctuating under various different constraints.  The combined character of the full animation appears as an "angry" mass with pent up body motion and sharp color contrasting edges.  

Outputs can be programmatically saved to a high quality gif download, which can be used as a unique animated profile picture (*for any service that allows animated gif images)

Featuring:
x10 different possible color schemes (4 with near-infinite variations!)
x4 different possible generative weight classes (each with significant variation)
x3 different accent coloring styles (two with significant variation)
x7 different generalized anger levels (affecting animation speeds)
x6 possible special extra accent detail styles
x5 different base shape constructions
x1 'base' generative algorithm *

= 25,200 possible base feature combinations!!  Some traits and combinations are more likely to appear than others...

* Not included in calculations: a near infinite variety of shape positions, sizes, and placements, and a wide spectrum of possible animation lengths!


--


Keyboard controls:

Press [1] to view at native resolution
Press [2] to view at high resolution
Press [0] to scale to default screen width

Press [S] to save a high quality gif!* (May take a couple seconds to render)

*Tested in Google Chrome browser only!  
Should work in others but please use the latest version of Chrome if encountering any issue.

metadata.name: The seed :: issue 1 #79
metadata.description:
*the seed* is an experimental project, meaning that we give ourselves permission to test the waters and see where the current takes us. *the seed* is also a zine, which suggests something both unpretentious and grassroots — it's most definitely a labor of love!

The first issue is on the minimalist side, with a total of 19 pages nonetheless! We avoided big blocks of text and leaned into finding creative solutions to allow the artists to express themselves without having to produce new work. We also elected not to systematically showcase an artist's latest project as a way of jumping off the cultural treadmill which has conditioned us to focus almost exclusively on "what's new" and "what's next". As a result, *the seed*, which we envisage as a quarterly publication, will hopefully convey a certain quality of timelessness.

This issue is a collective invitation to catch our breath and celebrate the beauty that has been brought forth by a diverse group of amazing artists from all over the world: Lammetje, Liam Egan, Ciput, Elsif & Clint Fulkerson. Instead of asking the typical interview questions, we invited each artist to introduce themselves using a text based recording device which allows the reader to witness the workings of the artist's mind. The result feels both lighthearted and intimate.

The edition size is 128 and statistically one in five coverpages will be an animated collage created using the artwork of one of our five artists. No two coverpages are alike as the seed differs for each collage. This might be less apparent if the project is only examined through thumbnails. Please take the time to explore all of the interactive features of *the seed* on full screen.

*the seed* was made with C++ and OpenGL and converted to the web via Emscripten.

Thank you for reading this metadata and for coming on this journey with us!

metadata.name: Anachronous #42
metadata.description:
This project is about the exploration of chaotic structures created with lines and blurry silhouettes. They work together to make the shapes emerge without revealing them completely and create dark and light areas that compose a feeling of depth and weight to the scene.

Some pieces are chaotic, some more ordered. Some have strong compositions, some don't. By zooming in on the details we can let our mind wander and start seeing shapes.

Best experienced in full-screen.

Press S to take a screenshot
Press M to take a high resolution screenshot
Press H to take a higher resolution screenshot (may not work for some devices)

WARNING: Project is using webgl, it may not work on some older devices.

Original artwork by William Watkins · Lyon, 2022

metadata.name: KONSTRUKTS #189
metadata.description:
A study of building and destroying. I built this. You may knock it over.

Humans are both creators and destroyers. One of the earliest games children learn to play is building with blocks, then knocking them down. This simple activity is teaching kids about gravity, cause and effect, and imposing their will on the world around them. As children grow older, the gap between these opposing actions widens. The intention behind knocking things down becomes less innocent, and creators aren't as excited to see their work destroyed.

In 1915, the Russian avant-garde founded the abstract art movement known as Constructivism, rejecting everything except for the absolute purest aspects of form and material. This art was used in service of the Russian revolution and utilized heavily in its propaganda, intended to highlight the utilitarian nature of industrial progress. Mainly, building the new Russia. Its influence is lasting, and can be seen throughout art and design trends even today.

When Russia invaded Ukraine in February of 2022, footage of missiles and airstrikes decimating Ukrainian buildings permeated the media. Ukrainian lives, kitchens, windowsill gardens, and family photos tumbled to the ground. Like children's blocks. Things that took a lifetime to build were destroyed in seconds. 

KONSTRUKTS represents this duality in creation and destruction. Stacked children's blocks are rendered in the style of Constructivist designs like El Lissitzky's Proun series, and Alexander Rodchenko's posters. With a simple tap, blocks (or buildings) can be knocked to the ground.

- Tap anywhere to reveal the KONSTRUKTS menu in the top left. Tap the menu for several options.
- KONSTRUKTS can be exported as USDZ or GLTF models to be used in augmented reality or the metaverse.
- Export a full resolution PNG image from the menu.
- If you knocked over the blocks, you can reset them from the menu.

KONSTRUKTS is built entirely with code, using Three.js, JavaScript, and GLSL.

metadata.name: Threads of destiny #62
metadata.description:
"Threads of destiny" is an abstract artwork focusing on the composition and color of elements. Each thread consists of a sequence of shapes that are placed together in a harmonious rhythm, just like our world where each of us, while being unique, together form a larger design, each of the shapes, on the threads of destiny, with the help of each other, make a larger and harmonious composition. 

Various sizes and densities and more than 12 color palettes have been used.

Press ’s’ on the live mode to save the artwork.
